photo.title: Bookplate of Gaspard Ernest Stroehlin (1844-1907) with the stamp of bookseller Alexander E. Seeligmüller (Seeligmueller)
photo.description: Bookplate of Gaspard Ernest Stroehlin (1844-1907), a Swiss minister and professor (specializing in church history) at the University of Geneva. "Mente libera" was his motto; "Champel" appears to be an allusion to Champel, Switzerland, where the reformer Michael Servetus was burned at the stake in 1553. The building in the background is probably St. Pierre Cathedral in Geneva, where Calvin famously preached. Hans Asper, whose name appears on this binding, bound at least one other of Stroehlin's books; cf. I. Krekler, Stammbücher bis 1625 (Wiesbaden: Harassowitz, 1999), p. 6 (nr. 2). photo.title: Woodcut ("Sauritt des Papsts") after Lucas Cranach the Elder, used by Christian Rödinger the Elder of Magdeburg, of the pope riding a sow, holding steaming excrement
photo.description: Woodcut ("Sauritt des Papsts") after Lucas Cranach the Elder, used by Christian Rödinger the Elder of Magdeburg. According to I. Gobry, it is a reproduction of a Cranach woodcut (no. 6) in Martin Luther's 1545 polemic Abbildung des Bapstum (cf. Image de la papauté (Grenoble: Millon, 1997), p. 118). R.W. Scribner unpacks the symbolism of the image in the context of Luther's intent to "discredit papal plans for a General Council of the Church": The pope rides on a sow, carrying a spiral of steaming excrement on his open palm. The Latin text at the top says this is how the pope holds a council in Germany. The German text states that the sow must allow itself to be ridden and spurred from both sides. There are two allusions here. Luther often spoke of Germany as the "papal sow", to be force-fed with papal lies for the pope's sole gain. There was also a popular riddle in circulation, and which appeared in print in 1541: "How do you ride a sow so that it does not bite? -- Put dung on your hand, and when the sow smells it, it will chase it and not bite the rider." The message, then, was that Germany may well seek a council from the pope, but all it could expect was lies and deceit. (Cf. For the Sake of Simple Folk: Popular Propaganda for the German Reformation (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1994), p. 82-83.) The image may also have anti-Semitic undertones, recalling satirical depictions of Jews riding on pigs (cf. R.W. Scribner, Popular Culture and Popular Movements in Reformation Germany (London: Hambledon Press, 1987), p. 292). For a thorough analysis of the Sauritt in anti-Semitic propaganda, see Birgit Wiedl, "Laughing at the Beast" in Laughter in the Middle Ages and Early Modern Times, ed. A. Classen (Berlin: De Gruyter, 2010), p. 323ff. Established heading: Cranach, Lucas,‏ ‎‡d 1472-1553‏ Established heading: Rödinger, Christian,‏ ‎‡d d. 1557‏ Penn Libraries call number: GC5 F5948 550e All images from this book

photo.title: Portion of an early parchment bifolium from a missal written in a Gothic bookhand
photo.description: Portion of an early parchment bifolium from a missal written in a Gothic bookhand in 2 columns frame-ruled in ink (first line of text below top line of ruling) with rubrics, 1- and 2-line initials, and capital strokes in red, 1 6-line initial T in blue and white (with additional decorative penwork in brown ink supplied by a later hand?), and a pair of stylized foliate border elements (one primarily in pink, the other primarily in green). Text visible in this image: left-hand column contains gospel reading from John 12:22-26; offertory (Ps. 95(96):6); and beginning of secret ("Accipe, quaesumus, Domine, munera dignanter oblata ..."); right-hand column contains end of secret (as above); communion (John 12:26); and postcommunion (here "Co[m]pl[e]n[dum].": "Sacro munere satiati supplices ... tuae sentiamus augmentum."), all possibly for one of the commons of martyrs, followed by the introit and oratio for the dedication of a church. Penn Libraries call number: GC5 F1125 532s All images from this book

photo.description: Upper inscription: Hieronymus Sauler Eccl Mosbac: Pastor [Hieronymus Sauler (1639-1716), schoolmaster at Ansbach and pastor at Mosbach, according to this entry in the catalog of the Staats- und Universitätsbibliothek Hamburg. According to this transcription of the appendix of the Gedenck-, Stadt- und Huth-Buch (Chronik der Stadt Feuchtwangen), Sauler served as pastor of Mosbach from 1674 until his death.] Lower inscription: Theophili Pauli Christii Coburgensis [Gottlieb Paul Christ (1707-1786), professor, librarian and court functionary at Ansbach. In their finding aid Aldine Press Books at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center, The University of Texas at Austin (Austin: The Center, 1998), Craig W. Kallendorf and Maria X. Wells identify the ex-libris "Theophili Pauli Christi" as "Gottlieb Paul Christ (18th cent.), prof. at Anspach Gymnasium". According to his biographical entry in C.A. Baader, Lexikon Verstorbener Schrifsteller des 18. und 19. Jahrhunderts (Augsburg: Von Jenisch- und Stage'schen Buchhandlung, 1825), Bd. 2, T. 1, p. 22, Christ was born in Coburg but came to Ansbach in 1728 to take service with Freiherr von Seckendorff (probably Christoph Ludwig Freiherr von Seckendorff-Aberdar). He went abroad on several diplomatic missions and became the librarian for the Ansbacher Schlossbibliothek. (According to E.F.C. Oertel in Georg Ludwig Oeder der erste Rektor bei der Einweihung des neuen Gymnasiums in Ansbach am 12. Juni 1737 ... photo.title: One leaf of a ms. bifolium (verso visible), containing glosses on Gregory's Decretals?
photo.description: Lower board: one leaf of a ms. bifolium (verso visible), containing glosses on Gregory's Decretals? Most entries open with the words "Nota quod"; the red-underlined headings appear to correspond to the opening word(s) of the chapter being glossed. Frame ruling visible; text written in brown ink in 2 columns of 36 lines (first line below top line of ruling) with red rubric, initials, paragraph marks, and underlines. In the left-hand column, the visible red-underlined headings correspond to the opening words of lib. 3, tit. 4, cap. 6-13: C{onsequente} De cet[er]o Ex parte Qualit[er] Int[er] q[ua]tuor Ex tue Tue Ex p[ar]te In the right-hand column, the first heading corresponds to the title of lib. 3, tit. 4, cap. 16: "Cum ad h[oc]". The next heading, "Clericos quida[m]," probably refers to cap. 17, which begins (in this edition, at least), "Clericos in ecclesiis tuae". The rubric "De p[re]bendis et dignitatibus" corresponds to the title of lib. 3, tit. 5, and the visible red-underlined headings which follow correspond to the opening words of the text of cap. 4-9: E{piscopus} Quia i[n] tantu[m] Cum tenea[mur] Refferente [sic] Maiorib[us] Relatu[m] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 D5668 524d 1525 All images from this book

photo.title: Austin Lamont (1905-1969)
photo.description: Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. photo.description: Bookplate: H. C. Hollway-Calthrop dated: Florence Dec. 1883 Inscription: A. Lamont Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. photo.title: H. Pfau, Winterthur (Switzerland); David Sulzer, 1706
photo.description: Inscription at head: H: Pfau Winterthur [The Pfau (="peacock") family of Wintherthur, Switzerland, were notable 17th- and early 18th-century potters, oven-makers and -painters. Five of its members active in their craft were named Hans Heinrich: Hans Heinrich I (1559-1636), Hans Heinrich II (1598-1673), Hans Heinrich III (1642-1719), Hans Heinrich IV (1672-1714), and Hans Heinrich V (fl. 1702-1740?). Cf. their entries in Schweizerisches Künsterlexikon (Frauenfeld: Huber & Co., 1905-1917), 2. Bd., p. 539f; cf. also the entry for the Pfau family in the online SIKART Lexikon und Datenbank zur Kunst in der Schweiz und im Fürstentum Liechtenstein.] Inscription at foot: nunc Davidis Sulzeri. 1706. ["Der beste Winterthurer Ofenmaler des 18. Jahrhunderts war David Sulzer (1716-1792). Er weist in reiner Blumenmalerei, in stilisiertem Blumenornament, in kleinen Landschaften auf Wege, die den ausschliesslichen Ofenschmuck seit der Mitte des 18. Jahrhunderts ausmachen sollten." -- M. Lüthi, Bürgerliche Innendekoration des Spätbarock und Rokoko in der deutschen Schweiz (Zürich: Art. Institut Orell Füssli, 1927), p. 43 (citing an article by a Dr. Hafner in Winterthurer Neujahrsblatt 1876). Sulzer is also mentioned in A. Jacquemart, History of the Ceramic Art, tr. B. Palliser (London: Sampson Low et al., 1873), p. 490, and an example of his work in collaboration with potter Ottmar Vogler of Elgg is briefly described in B. Bucher, ed., Geschichte der Technischen Künste, 3. Bd. (Stuttgart: Union Deutsche Verlagsgesellschaft, 1893), p. 478.] Getty records a David Sulzer 1685-1762 , a Swiss stove painter Penn Libraries call number: GC5 C4534 542d All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record
